WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.600 --> 00:00:03.790
Professor Robert
Shiller: First thing,

00:00:03.790 --> 00:00:06.778
I wanted just to--I forgot to
show--I don't know how exciting

00:00:06.778 --> 00:00:08.720
this is, but this is a ticker
tape.

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:12.974
They weren't brown.
This tape is about a

00:00:12.974 --> 00:00:16.491
half-century old.
It came from the attic of the

00:00:16.491 --> 00:00:19.792
New York Stock Exchange.
When I was at a conference

00:00:19.792 --> 00:00:22.350
there a year ago,
I mentioned to the vice

00:00:22.350 --> 00:00:25.994
president there that I had told
my class about ticker tape

00:00:25.994 --> 00:00:29.703
machines and they had never
heard of them--didn't know what

00:00:29.703 --> 00:00:31.916
they were;
well, at least some of them

00:00:31.916 --> 00:00:33.440
hadn't.
So, he sent me this.

00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:39.197
This was never used,
but normally it would go into a

00:00:39.197 --> 00:00:45.520
machine and it would print out
stock prices at trades.

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:48.886
I was giving a talk yesterday
at the New York Stock Exchange

00:00:48.886 --> 00:00:51.910
and I met him again and I said,
thank you for this;

00:00:51.910 --> 00:00:55.478
my class was happy to see it.
He said, well I could have

00:00:55.478 --> 00:00:57.560
given you a whole ticker tape
machine.

00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:01.545
He said, well the attic at the
New York Stock Exchange was

00:01:01.545 --> 00:01:04.622
filled with them,
but they finally threw them

00:01:04.622 --> 00:01:09.704
out, so it's too late.
I think it is--this is evidence

00:01:09.704 --> 00:01:15.286
that information technology
really has dominated stock

00:01:15.286 --> 00:01:18.200
prices.
We didn't really have active

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:20.792
stock markets before the
electronic age,

00:01:20.792 --> 00:01:24.448
which is an interesting thing
to think about because the

00:01:24.448 --> 00:01:28.170
ticker tape machine was invented
by Edison in 1867.

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:32.582
In 1867, there were hardly
any--there were stock markets,

00:01:32.582 --> 00:01:36.941
but they were very small.
It was really the electronic

00:01:36.941 --> 00:01:40.129
communications that made it what
it is.

00:01:40.129 --> 00:01:45.212
It's exciting to think about
the future and where electronic

00:01:45.212 --> 00:01:49.950
communication is going to take
markets going forward.

00:01:49.950 --> 00:01:56.220
I wanted to continue today
about our futures markets.

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:00.170
Let me just step back and
think, what is a futures market?

00:02:00.170 --> 00:02:04.053
Today, I'm going to talk about
how it has expanded to cover

00:02:04.053 --> 00:02:07.670
lots of other things,
notably financial instruments.

00:02:07.670 --> 00:02:11.150
Let's just think,
what is a futures market?

00:02:11.150 --> 00:02:16.083
If you read Holbrook Working,
who's on your reading list,

00:02:16.083 --> 00:02:21.165
and his half-century old paper,
back in those days that he was

00:02:21.165 --> 00:02:25.443
writing, he says that the name
"futures" is a bit misleading

00:02:25.443 --> 00:02:29.939
because that suggests that it's
talking about the future rather

00:02:29.939 --> 00:02:33.270
than today.
If you listen to the news about

00:02:33.270 --> 00:02:36.419
any commodity price,
it's always talking about

00:02:36.419 --> 00:02:39.918
futures price.
They don't talk about the price

00:02:39.918 --> 00:02:42.120
today.
The futures price is the

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:46.250
interesting--the point that
Working made is not so much that

00:02:46.250 --> 00:02:50.800
it's in the future is that it's
well-defined and standardized.

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:56.029
For agricultural futures,
it's true that the contract

00:02:56.029 --> 00:02:59.550
doesn't mature for a month or
so,

00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:05.031
but as Working points out,
any contract for delivery of

00:03:05.031 --> 00:03:09.322
something has some term.
They don't just deliver it

00:03:09.322 --> 00:03:12.562
instantly and Working says,
there are times when the

00:03:12.562 --> 00:03:16.502
so-called spot price is actually
further in the future than the

00:03:16.502 --> 00:03:19.337
futures price.
If you look at the way things

00:03:19.337 --> 00:03:22.200
are traded--I'm going to be
talking a lot about oil,

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:24.669
but let me just talk generally
about oil.

00:03:24.669 --> 00:03:28.071
What is the price of oil and
how does anybody know what it

00:03:28.071 --> 00:03:31.128
is?
If you go to people who buy and

00:03:31.128 --> 00:03:36.379
sell oil, they will tell you,
well we don't just sell oil;

00:03:36.379 --> 00:03:38.690
we don't just have it ready to
go.

00:03:38.690 --> 00:03:43.664
Almost all of the oil is sold
in long-term contracts,

00:03:43.664 --> 00:03:49.499
so an oil company will sell a
contract to deliver regularly to

00:03:49.499 --> 00:03:51.699
some refinery,
oil.

00:03:51.699 --> 00:03:55.302
They'll have these tankers
appear and we sign a five-year

00:03:55.302 --> 00:03:58.840
contract--or whatever--and it
has all kinds of terms.

00:03:58.840 --> 00:04:02.456
If you read the contract it
would be fifty pages long and it

00:04:02.456 --> 00:04:06.380
would specify all kinds of "what
we'll do if we don't deliver" or

00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:10.120
"what happens if we can't
deliver the grade we promised."

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:13.685
Lots of uncertainties are
defined, so who knows what the

00:04:13.685 --> 00:04:17.769
price of oil is when it's being
part of a long-term contract.

00:04:17.769 --> 00:04:22.589
That's why you need a futures
market and the futures market is

00:04:22.589 --> 00:04:27.329
the market that's free of--it
has a standardized contract.

00:04:27.329 --> 00:04:32.215
We know exactly what the price
means and attention focuses on

00:04:32.215 --> 00:04:36.693
the futures market because the
trade there is--everybody

00:04:36.693 --> 00:04:39.642
understands it;
everyone knows exactly what's

00:04:39.642 --> 00:04:41.904
being traded.
The minute-to-minute changes

00:04:41.904 --> 00:04:45.302
reflect something;
they reflect something real,

00:04:45.302 --> 00:04:50.031
namely change in the market not
any change in what's being

00:04:50.031 --> 00:04:53.683
delivered.
Anyway, it used to be that the

00:04:53.683 --> 00:04:57.544
only futures markets were for
commodities--for

00:04:57.544 --> 00:05:03.034
things--typically it was thought
that futures markets are good to

00:05:03.034 --> 00:05:08.181
have for things that are not
standardized--that are difficult

00:05:08.181 --> 00:05:11.268
to define.
So, we want rice futures and we

00:05:11.268 --> 00:05:14.525
want wheat futures because there
are so many different kinds of

00:05:14.525 --> 00:05:16.889
rice in different areas and
different--so,

00:05:16.889 --> 00:05:22.220
we want to have a standardized
price.

00:05:22.220 --> 00:05:27.603
There were no financial futures
until the 1970s and people felt

00:05:27.603 --> 00:05:32.206
back then that we don't need
futures contracts because

00:05:32.206 --> 00:05:35.680
there's a standardization of
shares.

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:39.310
Every share in a given company
is exactly identical.

00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:41.407
When you say,
I'd like to buy a hundred

00:05:41.407 --> 00:05:44.002
shares of a company,
you're not going to ask the

00:05:44.002 --> 00:05:46.210
broker, well which shares did I
get?

00:05:46.210 --> 00:05:49.797
And can I look at them?
Your broker would say in

00:05:49.797 --> 00:05:52.230
disbelief, look you've got
shares;

00:05:52.230 --> 00:05:55.100
they're all absolutely
identical.

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:59.091
You might think there's no need
for a futures market because the

00:05:59.091 --> 00:06:02.449
prices are already standardized
in the cash market.

00:06:02.449 --> 00:06:05.921
Moreover, the prices that you
see traded on the stock exchange

00:06:05.921 --> 00:06:08.880
floor--you know exactly when the
trade took place;

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:13.040
they're not future-traded.
Why did we get futures markets?

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:16.835
Let me come back to that.
Let me just first--why did we

00:06:16.835 --> 00:06:21.024
get stock futures markets?
Let me come back to that and

00:06:21.024 --> 00:06:24.449
talk about--let's be clear what
they are.

00:06:24.449 --> 00:06:30.071
Stock index futures markets
came in around 1980 and one of

00:06:30.071 --> 00:06:35.693
the very first was the Standard
&amp; Poor 500 Stock Index

00:06:35.693 --> 00:06:41.709
Futures Market traded at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.

00:06:41.709 --> 00:06:47.577
It was a radical innovation
when it came in because people

00:06:47.577 --> 00:06:52.877
thought, what's the point?
I can see farmers delivering

00:06:52.877 --> 00:06:57.972
their corn or their oats or
whatever, but stocks--what's the

00:06:57.972 --> 00:07:00.307
point?
Well, it turned out to be

00:07:00.307 --> 00:07:03.795
absolutely right because--the
CME was absolutely right to

00:07:03.795 --> 00:07:06.910
create this market
because--within a few years,

00:07:06.910 --> 00:07:10.783
there was more trade on the
futures market than there was on

00:07:10.783 --> 00:07:14.034
the stock market itself.
Let's be clear what they

00:07:14.034 --> 00:07:18.089
created--and this is the terms
of the contract as it is today.

00:07:18.089 --> 00:07:22.721
The S&amp;P 500 is an index of
stock prices produced by

00:07:22.721 --> 00:07:25.809
Standard &amp;
Poor's Corporation and

00:07:25.809 --> 00:07:30.527
it's--they take the prices of
500 stocks and they form a

00:07:30.527 --> 00:07:34.016
weighted average.
It's an arithmetic average

00:07:34.016 --> 00:07:37.573
where the weights correspond to
the amounts outstanding of the

00:07:37.573 --> 00:07:40.490
various stocks,
so it's a value-weighted index.

00:07:40.490 --> 00:07:47.434
It's just a number published by
the American Stock Exchange--no,

00:07:47.434 --> 00:07:50.410
by Standard &amp;
Poor's.

00:07:50.410 --> 00:07:55.848
All it is at--just as with
agricultural futures--I don't

00:07:55.848 --> 00:08:00.200
know how clear I was about this
yesterday.

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:04.543
If you--maybe I didn't say this.
Let me say that it applies to

00:08:04.543 --> 00:08:08.300
both agricultural futures and
financial futures.

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:12.729
If you want to trade in the
futures market,

00:08:12.729 --> 00:08:19.161
you have to put up margin and
there's a margin requirement for

00:08:19.161 --> 00:08:22.914
each contract.
The margin is there to

00:08:22.914 --> 00:08:27.129
eliminate counterparty risk with
other contracts.

00:08:27.129 --> 00:08:31.822
When you sign a contract with
another person you have to worry

00:08:31.822 --> 00:08:34.899
whether that person will come
through,

00:08:34.899 --> 00:08:40.700
but with the exchange that
counterparty risk is eliminated.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:45.721
The way the exchange eliminates
it is it takes the other side

00:08:45.721 --> 00:08:50.324
itself--of every contract
who--it stands between you and

00:08:50.324 --> 00:08:55.679
the counterparty and it protects
itself by demanding margin.

00:08:55.679 --> 00:09:00.693
You have to,
up front, put up margin for any

00:09:00.693 --> 00:09:06.639
futures contract and the margin
is settled daily.

00:09:06.639 --> 00:09:12.283
Every day, they look at your
margin account and they adjust

00:09:12.283 --> 00:09:14.708
it.
So, if--let me go back to wheat

00:09:14.708 --> 00:09:18.271
futures because that's the
simpler--I don't think I really

00:09:18.271 --> 00:09:22.376
explained this well.
If you buy--when we say "buy

00:09:22.376 --> 00:09:25.899
wheat futures," what does that
mean?

00:09:25.899 --> 00:09:30.349
That means--the word buy or
sell has a different meaning in

00:09:30.349 --> 00:09:33.642
futures markets.
When you buy wheat futures or,

00:09:33.642 --> 00:09:36.128
for that matter,
S&amp;P 500 in futures,

00:09:36.128 --> 00:09:38.360
it means that you put up
margin.

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:41.210
You did not pay the price for
the contract;

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:46.350
you only paid margin,
which might be 5% or less than

00:09:46.350 --> 00:09:50.222
the price.
If you're buying wheat futures,

00:09:50.222 --> 00:09:54.124
what are you doing?
You're putting up margin and

00:09:54.124 --> 00:09:58.182
standing ready to see your
margin account credited or

00:09:58.182 --> 00:10:03.097
debited depending on the change
in the futures price from day to

00:10:03.097 --> 00:10:05.721
day.
If the price of wheat in the

00:10:05.721 --> 00:10:08.809
futures market goes up and you
bought futures,

00:10:08.809 --> 00:10:12.857
they will increase your margin
account by the amount that it

00:10:12.857 --> 00:10:15.838
went up.
If the price of wheat goes

00:10:15.838 --> 00:10:20.576
down, they will decrease your
margin account balance by that

00:10:20.576 --> 00:10:22.350
amount.
How do they get the money?

00:10:22.350 --> 00:10:26.215
Well, that's because for every
buyer there's a seller in the

00:10:26.215 --> 00:10:29.360
futures market,
so somebody else sold futures.

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:32.352
Both of you put up margin;
if you are buying,

00:10:32.352 --> 00:10:34.705
you put up margin;
if you are selling,

00:10:34.705 --> 00:10:38.150
you put up margin.
So, the result is that they

00:10:38.150 --> 00:10:42.781
have a place to get the money.
If the price goes up and you

00:10:42.781 --> 00:10:45.870
bought, your margin account will
go up.

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:49.338
The exchange will get the money
by taking it from the margin

00:10:49.338 --> 00:10:52.983
account of the guy who sold and
they've always fixed it so that

00:10:52.983 --> 00:10:56.570
the number of buyers always
equals the number of sellers.

00:10:56.570 --> 00:11:00.540
You see how the exchange can't
lose and you can't lose;

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:07.224
this is a guaranteed thing.
The only problem is that what

00:11:07.224 --> 00:11:13.227
if a margin account runs dry?
Both buyer and seller have put

00:11:13.227 --> 00:11:16.983
up margin and then the
price--let's say the price drops

00:11:16.983 --> 00:11:19.710
a lot;
the futures price drops a lot.

00:11:19.710 --> 00:11:28.606
Then, that means that the
buyer's margin account is wiped

00:11:28.606 --> 00:11:31.547
out.
What will happen then is that

00:11:31.547 --> 00:11:35.864
the futures commission merchant
will go to the person who bought

00:11:35.864 --> 00:11:41.035
the futures and say,
do you want to post more margin

00:11:41.035 --> 00:11:45.210
or do you want me to close you
out?

00:11:45.210 --> 00:11:49.476
That person has a decision to
make and if he or she puts up

00:11:49.476 --> 00:11:53.301
more margin, then that
replenishes the margin account

00:11:53.301 --> 00:11:57.937
and the person can keep trading.
That's how the exchanges

00:11:57.937 --> 00:12:02.573
eliminate counterparty risk,
by daily resettlement of the

00:12:02.573 --> 00:12:05.126
contracts.
It's an invention--actually

00:12:05.126 --> 00:12:07.356
goes back to Japan;
although, it was slightly

00:12:07.356 --> 00:12:09.797
different in form.
It's an invention that

00:12:09.797 --> 00:12:13.812
eliminates any risk of the
counterparty not performing so

00:12:13.812 --> 00:12:17.820
that risk doesn't affect price.
So it's the same--are you clear

00:12:17.820 --> 00:12:20.000
on that now--how the margin
account works?

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.343
You might not enjoy this.
Depends on how much of a

00:12:23.343 --> 00:12:26.539
gambling instinct for how much
fun this is.

00:12:26.539 --> 00:12:30.744
If you buy or sell futures,
you can expect a phone call

00:12:30.744 --> 00:12:33.470
from your broker sooner or
later;

00:12:33.470 --> 00:12:37.330
well, not necessarily,
unless you have incredibly good

00:12:37.330 --> 00:12:38.851
luck.
Hillary Clinton,

00:12:38.851 --> 00:12:41.317
when she invested in the
futures market,

00:12:41.317 --> 00:12:45.019
she had incredibly good luck.
You know this story?

00:12:45.019 --> 00:12:47.525
When her husband,
Bill Clinton,

00:12:47.525 --> 00:12:51.032
was Governor,
she got a call from--a friend

00:12:51.032 --> 00:12:56.125
recommended to her a very good
broker who knew how to trade in

00:12:56.125 --> 00:13:00.706
commodity futures.
So, she put up something like

00:13:00.706 --> 00:13:06.302
$1,000 of her own money and then
the broker kept calling her and

00:13:06.302 --> 00:13:09.500
asking her what she wanted to
do.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:15.722
She just never lost anything;
she turned it into a $100,000

00:13:15.722 --> 00:13:19.710
within a year and then she
stopped.

00:13:19.710 --> 00:13:22.850
We don't know why--I'm not
anti-Hillary Clinton;

00:13:22.850 --> 00:13:24.889
this is just a futures market
story.

00:13:24.889 --> 00:13:28.461
I like her a lot,
but what do you think happened

00:13:28.461 --> 00:13:30.506
there?
Her margin account just kept

00:13:30.506 --> 00:13:31.840
going up, and up,
and up.

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:35.980
I mean, it went up amazingly.
You could conclude that she is

00:13:35.980 --> 00:13:39.538
a brilliant trader and she ought
to be President of the United

00:13:39.538 --> 00:13:42.980
States, but then the next
question is, why did she stop?

00:13:42.980 --> 00:13:46.680
Why did she run it for a
hundred-fold increase and stop?

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:50.376
Does anyone have any idea?
Is this common knowledge--this

00:13:50.376 --> 00:13:51.760
story?
Well, the story ends there;

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:57.057
nobody knows what happened.
Futures traders are willing to

00:13:57.057 --> 00:14:00.240
exercise a guess of what
happened.

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:04.649
Does anyone have any guess what
you think happened?

00:14:04.649 --> 00:14:07.990
Well, I shouldn't say things so
political.

00:14:07.990 --> 00:14:11.653
I do like Hillary Clinton,
but what likely happened is

00:14:11.653 --> 00:14:15.731
some futures commission merchant
was thinking of bribing the

00:14:15.731 --> 00:14:19.281
Governor.
Maybe he didn't--never actually

00:14:19.281 --> 00:14:24.071
did it--but let's do a little
favor for his wife and then

00:14:24.071 --> 00:14:27.750
maybe I can ask him for
something later.

00:14:27.750 --> 00:14:31.873
So, the futures merchant just
didn't listen carefully to what

00:14:31.873 --> 00:14:33.942
she said.
He just--well,

00:14:33.942 --> 00:14:39.849
he sort of cooked the books and
gave her money by making it look

00:14:39.849 --> 00:14:42.771
like a trade.
When she found out--what

00:14:42.771 --> 00:14:45.081
finally likely happened is
someone said,

00:14:45.081 --> 00:14:48.279
do you think you're making so
much money in the futures

00:14:48.279 --> 00:14:50.828
market?
Remember who your husband is

00:14:50.828 --> 00:14:54.990
and this guy--do you trust him?
This is a likely guess.

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:58.080
She finally wondered,
what is going on here?

00:14:58.080 --> 00:15:00.990
And she stopped because she
didn't know what was happening

00:15:00.990 --> 00:15:03.872
either.
Somehow money was coming in

00:15:03.872 --> 00:15:08.807
and--that's the very--now,
maybe she was just very savvy

00:15:08.807 --> 00:15:12.805
in her investing ability,
but usually your futures

00:15:12.805 --> 00:15:16.210
accounts go both up and down and
you get margin calls.

00:15:21.879 --> 00:15:25.938
Anyway, the last day of the
contract there's a settlement

00:15:25.938 --> 00:15:30.141
and--in agricultural futures,
the last day there's delivery

00:15:30.141 --> 00:15:35.566
if you're still in the contract.
If you are a seller on the last

00:15:35.566 --> 00:15:40.564
day, you must deliver the
specified number of barrels or

00:15:40.564 --> 00:15:44.977
bushels of whatever it is.
Or, if you are a buyer,

00:15:44.977 --> 00:15:49.177
you must take delivery of them.
With stock futures it's

00:15:49.177 --> 00:15:54.059
different because nobody expects
you to deliver shares of stock.

00:15:54.059 --> 00:16:00.805
What happens on the last day is
there's a final settlement and

00:16:00.805 --> 00:16:07.108
that is in dollars in this
case--250 times the S&amp;P 500

00:16:07.108 --> 00:16:13.854
Index on the last day minus the
futures price of the preceding

00:16:13.854 --> 00:16:17.480
day;
that's the settlement.

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:20.939
Of course, you have been
gaining the changes in the

00:16:20.939 --> 00:16:23.500
futures prices every preceding
day.

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:28.956
If you--this is what you
receive as a buyer if you bought

00:16:28.956 --> 00:16:34.023
the contract and this is what
you pay if you sold the

00:16:34.023 --> 00:16:37.245
contract.
Everyday between the time you

00:16:37.245 --> 00:16:40.278
originally bought,
you've been getting--if you

00:16:40.278 --> 00:16:44.526
were a buyer--the change in the
futures price and at the end you

00:16:44.526 --> 00:16:47.558
get this.
If you sum all those up--all

00:16:47.558 --> 00:16:51.883
the settlements you got since
you bought the contract until

00:16:51.883 --> 00:16:55.687
the expiration of the
contract--you would be getting

00:16:55.687 --> 00:17:00.610
the index at time T minus
the futures when you bought.

00:17:00.610 --> 00:17:04.479
That defines it.
Everyday you get the change in

00:17:04.479 --> 00:17:07.756
the futures price;
those all add up into your

00:17:07.756 --> 00:17:11.819
margin account and on the last
day you get this.

00:17:11.819 --> 00:17:13.170
What is it, really,
you're doing?

00:17:13.170 --> 00:17:16.630
You could say--and they
wouldn't like to put this way at

00:17:16.630 --> 00:17:19.970
the futures exchanges;
they don't like gambling

00:17:19.970 --> 00:17:24.849
analogies, but I make gambling
analogies freely in this course.

00:17:24.849 --> 00:17:29.170
It's like placing a bet on the
stock market.

00:17:29.170 --> 00:17:32.040
If you think the stock market
is going to go up,

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:35.093
you buy the futures,
and if you think it's going to

00:17:35.093 --> 00:17:39.259
go down, you sell the futures.
If you buy one contract,

00:17:39.259 --> 00:17:42.727
how much money do you get?
You get, in total,

00:17:42.727 --> 00:17:46.018
over the total interval,
between the purchase date and

00:17:46.018 --> 00:17:50.333
the expiration of the contract,
you get the stock index minus

00:17:50.333 --> 00:17:53.980
the initial futures price you
paid, times $250;

00:17:53.980 --> 00:18:00.012
that's the gamble.
If you sell,

00:18:00.012 --> 00:18:08.981
it's just exactly the opposite.
Now, there's something called

00:18:08.981 --> 00:18:13.259
fair value and you'll see this
talked about a lot in futures.

00:18:13.259 --> 00:18:16.569
This is what the futures price
should be;

00:18:16.569 --> 00:18:20.160
we talked about it in terms of
wheat.

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:25.024
Remember, the fair value of a
wheat futures was equal to the

00:18:25.024 --> 00:18:29.393
price of wheat today times one
plus the interest rate,

00:18:29.393 --> 00:18:33.417
plus the storage costs;
that was the formula we had

00:18:33.417 --> 00:18:36.279
last time.
That was the fair value because

00:18:36.279 --> 00:18:40.605
we concluded that somebody who's
storing grain has to make their

00:18:40.605 --> 00:18:42.965
expenses,
they have to make the interest

00:18:42.965 --> 00:18:45.319
cost and they have to make the
storage costs,

00:18:45.319 --> 00:18:49.819
so the futures price should be
equal to fair value.

00:18:49.819 --> 00:18:53.599
It's the same here with stock
index futures.

00:18:53.599 --> 00:18:59.591
The fair value F of a
futures contract is equal to the

00:18:59.591 --> 00:19:05.183
stock price plus the stock price
times the interest rate,

00:19:05.183 --> 00:19:09.998
plus the storage cost.
The storage cost for stocks is

00:19:09.998 --> 00:19:14.730
negative because it doesn't cost
you anything to store a stock.

00:19:14.730 --> 00:19:16.759
Well, you don't even have to
store certificates anymore;

00:19:16.759 --> 00:19:19.390
your name will be held
electronically.

00:19:19.390 --> 00:19:23.569
It's negative because you get
dividends.

00:19:23.569 --> 00:19:29.240
So, y is the dividend
yield that you get on the stock.

00:19:29.240 --> 00:19:33.670
So r minus y is
the adjustment you have to make.

00:19:33.670 --> 00:19:37.652
You see this--to get from stock
price to fair value--you see

00:19:37.652 --> 00:19:40.960
this is the same formula that we
had for wheat,

00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:45.866
except that you understand that
storage costs for stocks are

00:19:45.866 --> 00:19:49.109
negative because they pay a
dividend.

00:19:49.109 --> 00:19:52.879
So, all I've done is I've--the
way I wrote it before was P x

00:19:52.879 --> 00:19:55.920
(1 + r + s) in the
preceding lecture;

00:19:55.920 --> 00:20:01.503
now it's P x (1 + r
â€“ y) because s =

00:20:01.503 --> 00:20:07.033
-y.
That's the fair value of a

00:20:07.033 --> 00:20:13.031
stock index futures.
Now, we said last time that

00:20:13.031 --> 00:20:17.989
sometimes prices deviate from
fair value--or maybe they don't

00:20:17.989 --> 00:20:21.460
depending on how you define fair
value.

00:20:21.460 --> 00:20:25.029
But, if you define fair value
as 1 + r + s, where

00:20:25.029 --> 00:20:27.819
s is just the cost of a
warehouse,

00:20:27.819 --> 00:20:31.954
then sometimes that formula
doesn't work because we talked

00:20:31.954 --> 00:20:35.052
about last time,
at the end of the growing

00:20:35.052 --> 00:20:37.920
season nobody is storing wheat
anymore.

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:44.699
So, the wheat market falls into
backwardation and the futures

00:20:44.699 --> 00:20:49.639
price gets low.
Other than that--normally wheat

00:20:49.639 --> 00:20:53.924
is being stored,
so normally wheat prices are

00:20:53.924 --> 00:20:59.671
essentially equal to fair value,
but stocks are always being

00:20:59.671 --> 00:21:03.169
stored.
There's no--it would be unusual

00:21:03.169 --> 00:21:05.950
to see backwardation in this
market;

00:21:05.950 --> 00:21:09.420
it would be abnormal because
we're always storing stocks.

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:11.859
That's what we do with them is
we hold them.

00:21:11.859 --> 00:21:15.300
Dividend yield--you can have
backwardation,

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:20.052
however, if the dividend yield
is greater than the interest

00:21:20.052 --> 00:21:24.968
rate because then the adjustment
would make the futures price

00:21:24.968 --> 00:21:29.448
below the cash price.
Otherwise, you can't have

00:21:29.448 --> 00:21:34.619
backwardation in this market,
so price should always equal

00:21:34.619 --> 00:21:39.009
fair value.
Right now, we're in an unusual

00:21:39.009 --> 00:21:45.458
circumstance where the interest
rate and the dividend yield are

00:21:45.458 --> 00:21:49.363
about the same.
Right now, the Fed has cut

00:21:49.363 --> 00:21:53.116
short-term interest
