00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:24.589
It's actually a very simple
market to understand.

00:27:24.589 --> 00:27:28.836
Once you know this formula you
pretty much know the price for

00:27:28.836 --> 00:27:31.989
any future date.
Remember the r again,

00:27:31.989 --> 00:27:35.949
as in the preceding lecture,
is not the annual interest rate

00:27:35.949 --> 00:27:39.708
unless we're talking about a
contract that matures in one

00:27:39.708 --> 00:27:43.705
year.
It's the interest between now

00:27:43.705 --> 00:27:50.470
and the expiration date and the
same thing with dividends.

00:27:50.470 --> 00:27:53.254
This is the dividend yield
where we're not talking about

00:27:53.254 --> 00:27:56.921
annual dividend yield,
but the dividends as a fraction

00:27:56.921 --> 00:28:01.269
of the price between now and
maturity of the contract.

00:28:01.269 --> 00:28:06.119
That's the only formula that we
really need.

00:28:06.119 --> 00:28:08.980
Let's think of the stock index
