00:42:33.167 --> 00:42:38.330
in ten years;
it's a huge surprise.

00:42:38.330 --> 00:42:45.266
There are other surprises.
One thing I wanted to do was to

00:42:45.266 --> 00:42:54.907
go through just a few--go
through a few stories about oil

00:42:54.907 --> 00:42:59.782
prices here.
This was a period when oil was

00:42:59.782 --> 00:43:03.192
generally very stable.
In the post World War II

00:43:03.192 --> 00:43:06.840
period, there was a Texas
Railroad Commission that was

00:43:06.840 --> 00:43:09.407
stabilizing oil prices.
At that time,

00:43:09.407 --> 00:43:11.800
the U.S.
was not a big importer of oil;

00:43:11.800 --> 00:43:17.080
we had our own oil supply and
we tended to--we had sort of a

00:43:17.080 --> 00:43:22.630
monopoly that tried to stabilize
the price and they were pretty

00:43:22.630 --> 00:43:26.300
successful for this long time
period.

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:32.093
The huge shock came--and this
is called the first oil

00:43:32.093 --> 00:43:38.179
shock--and that was in 1973-74.
Oil went up;

00:43:38.179 --> 00:43:42.889
it more than doubled--almost
three times increase in oil

00:43:42.889 --> 00:43:47.570
prices all of a sudden.
That was associated with a

00:43:47.570 --> 00:43:52.552
particular--it's called the
first oil crisis--and it

00:43:52.552 --> 00:43:58.414
coincides with the Yom Kippur
War between Israel and her Arab

00:43:58.414 --> 00:44:02.100
neighbors.
It caused a--Israel quickly

00:44:02.100 --> 00:44:05.883
triumphed in that war,
but it left a lot of bad

00:44:05.883 --> 00:44:10.241
feelings among the surrounding
Arab countries who were

00:44:10.241 --> 00:44:13.860
sympathetic with the Palestinian
cause,

00:44:13.860 --> 00:44:18.090
so they cut back on their oil
production.

00:44:18.090 --> 00:44:28.032
We have an organization called
OPEC--that's the Organization of

00:44:28.032 --> 00:44:34.447
Petroleum Exporting
Countries--and it was

00:44:34.447 --> 00:44:44.389
established in 1960 with a small
number of Arab countries,

00:44:44.389 --> 00:44:53.233
but it has gradually grown and
has more and more countries that

00:44:53.233 --> 00:44:57.528
are members.
It was OPEC that constrained

00:44:57.528 --> 00:45:01.139
the supply of oil for the first
oil crisis.

00:45:01.139 --> 00:45:08.690
This is the second oil crisis
here and that was in 1979-80.

00:45:08.690 --> 00:45:12.516
This again had its origin--at
least the common story and there

00:45:12.516 --> 00:45:17.675
must be some truth to the story.
It had its origin in another

00:45:17.675 --> 00:45:23.943
crisis in the Middle East and
that was the war between Iraq

00:45:23.943 --> 00:45:27.731
and Iran.
There was an Iranian revolution

00:45:27.731 --> 00:45:32.795
in 1979, where the Shah of Iran
was thrown out and the Ayatollah

00:45:32.795 --> 00:45:37.779
Khomeini came in and Iraq used
this as an opportunity to try to

00:45:37.779 --> 00:45:43.511
grab some oil from Iran.
This war completely disrupted

00:45:43.511 --> 00:45:50.550
oil supplies and we had this
huge spike in oil prices then.

00:45:50.550 --> 00:45:53.340
A lot of these spikes seem to
have political causes;

00:45:53.340 --> 00:45:59.969
this spike in the oil price is
caused by the 1991 invasion of

00:45:59.969 --> 00:46:06.929
the--well, the United States was
the primary invader of Iraq.

00:46:06.929 --> 00:46:13.512
This was after September 11th
and this disrupted oil supplies

00:46:13.512 --> 00:46:16.570
again.
All these times were periods of

00:46:16.570 --> 00:46:20.580
backwardation in the oil market
because people saw them as

00:46:20.580 --> 00:46:24.449
crises that were limiting the
supply of oil for now,

00:46:24.449 --> 00:46:30.660
but would eventually correct
themselves.

00:46:30.660 --> 00:46:36.949
What's happening now?
This is just an amazing spike

00:46:36.949 --> 00:46:40.587
of oil right now.
There isn't--we have this war

00:46:40.587 --> 00:46:45.364
in Iraq, but it's not a sudden,
intense thing that--it's not

00:46:45.364 --> 00:46:50.739
disrupting oil supplies.
So, why are we seeing this huge

00:46:50.739 --> 00:46:54.309
spike in oil?
That is an interesting question.

00:46:54.309 --> 00:46:58.675
Part of it has to do with the
fact that we have a rapidly

00:46:58.675 --> 00:47:03.041
growing world economy and
developing countries are moving

00:47:03.041 --> 00:47:06.159
forward faster than was
anticipated.

00:47:06.159 --> 00:47:10.485
So, there's a lot of demand for
oil from India,

00:47:10.485 --> 00:47:15.000
China, and other rapidly
developing countries.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:20.674
They say that China builds a
new city the size of Houston,

00:47:20.674 --> 00:47:25.353
Texas every month,
so they're consuming an awful

00:47:25.353 --> 00:47:30.211
lot of energy to do this.
The other side of it is that

00:47:30.211 --> 00:47:33.309
discoveries of oil have been
disappointing.

00:47:33.309 --> 00:47:37.354
I was just down in Mexico and
the President Calderon is

00:47:37.354 --> 00:47:41.923
talking about privatizing the
Mexican oil--or at least part of

00:47:41.923 --> 00:47:46.491
it--oil industry because they
have been disappointing in their

00:47:46.491 --> 00:47:49.795
exploration.
They're not finding oil,

00:47:49.795 --> 00:47:55.090
so the reserves that Mexico has
been actually declining rapidly.

00:47:55.090 --> 00:47:59.960
This brings up another thing
about the ownership of oil.

00:47:59.960 --> 00:48:05.280
I just wanted to mention
nationalization.

00:48:05.280 --> 00:48:10.389
It used to be that most of the
oil in the world was owned by

00:48:10.389 --> 00:48:13.420
private companies or
individuals,

00:48:13.420 --> 00:48:18.186
but nationalization began in
1938 in Mexico,

00:48:18.186 --> 00:48:25.169
where a left-leaning government
decided that all the Mexican oil

00:48:25.169 --> 00:48:31.598
that was owned by foreigners
really belonged to the Mexican

00:48:31.598 --> 00:48:35.985
people.
So, the Mexican government just

00:48:35.985 --> 00:48:40.614
said, it's ours.
That was an outrageous thing to

00:48:40.614 --> 00:48:46.449
say then, but it was greeted by
shock by international law.

00:48:46.449 --> 00:48:50.380
They just took the oil in their
country, saying that it wasn't

00:48:50.380 --> 00:48:56.554
fair the way it was sold.
It was followed up in 1951 by

00:48:56.554 --> 00:49:03.130
Iran and other countries
followed as well.

00:49:03.130 --> 00:49:07.204
Now we're seeing a reverse.
Mexico nationalized its oil in

00:49:07.204 --> 00:49:11.688
1938, but now that the supply is
dwindling, President Calderon

00:49:11.688 --> 00:49:17.219
wants to reverse the process;
this is controversial now.

00:49:17.219 --> 00:49:21.087
In yesterday's newspaper--I
don't know if you read The

00:49:21.087 --> 00:49:25.438
Wall Street Journal--it had
a story saying that Russian--for

00:49:25.438 --> 00:49:29.140
the first quarter of 2008,
Russian production of oil

00:49:29.140 --> 00:49:31.880
declined for the first time in
ten years.

00:49:31.880 --> 00:49:36.199
There's worry now that Russia
is running out of oil.

00:49:36.199 --> 00:49:40.889
I think it's these--this impact
of--news like this is having a

00:49:40.889 --> 00:49:45.579
psychological effect on the
market and it's causing a huge,

00:49:45.579 --> 00:49:50.181
well, you might consider this a
bubble in oil prices,

00:49:50.181 --> 00:49:53.810
but I'm not so sure that it's a
bubble.

00:49:53.810 --> 00:49:59.733
It's certainly unprecedented.
It seems like we're entering a

00:49:59.733 --> 00:50:01.369
period of great market
volatility.

00:50:01.369 --> 00:50:06.786
We've seen an unprecedented
bubble in home prices and now

00:50:06.786 --> 00:50:12.300
the economy is reeling from the
effects of this bubble.

00:50:12.300 --> 00:50:15.190
Look what's happening,
as well, in oil prices.

00:50:15.190 --> 00:50:17.450
Once again, there's no war
right now;

00:50:17.450 --> 00:50:22.230
there's nothing really dramatic.
We do have--you could call it a

00:50:22.230 --> 00:50:27.329
war, but it's not something that
has shut down the Persian Gulf

00:50:27.329 --> 00:50:33.170
and closed off oil supplies.
So, it seems like it's

00:50:33.170 --> 00:50:40.019
something more systemic.
It's something more to do with

00:50:40.019 --> 00:50:45.305
the economic situation than
before or it's something

00:50:45.305 --> 00:50:48.157
speculative.
We have--so we have

00:50:48.157 --> 00:50:50.958
backwardation,
but it's not a whole lot of

00:50:50.958 --> 00:50:55.361
backwardation.
They're still predicting oil

00:50:55.361 --> 00:51:02.424
prices to come down to something
like there--well over $100 in

00:51:02.424 --> 00:51:09.718
eight years--so it's not a--it's
not something that's related to

00:51:09.718 --> 00:51:15.969
a particular crisis that is
going to end quickly.

00:51:15.969 --> 00:51:22.082
I wanted to go--this just is a
clipping I got from--this was

00:51:22.082 --> 00:51:27.780
the day that Saddam Hussein
announced an oil embargo.

00:51:27.780 --> 00:51:36.690
This was his reaction to the
United States' pressure on him

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:43.603
and so oil prices spiked up.
It seemed dramatic when I made

00:51:43.603 --> 00:51:47.059
this clipping,
but now oil is $100 a barrel;

00:51:47.059 --> 00:51:51.078
that's only six years ago,
but at that time people

00:51:51.078 --> 00:51:56.327
thought--the market thought that
oil prices were coming back down

00:51:56.327 --> 00:51:58.530
by '03.
They were really wrong;

