people didn't get it.
All this time,

00:52:01.450 --> 00:52:05.386
people thought that oil--a
large part of the time it was in

00:52:05.386 --> 00:52:08.172
backwardation.
They thought there was some

00:52:08.172 --> 00:52:12.041
special event occurring--this is
Saddam Hussein--but it turns out

00:52:12.041 --> 00:52:14.579
that there was something driving
it up.

00:52:14.579 --> 00:52:17.800
This is again--this is natural
gas on that same date.

00:52:17.800 --> 00:52:21.142
This is still in contango
because the prices are going up

00:52:21.142 --> 00:52:23.529
through time,
so that kind of explains if

00:52:23.529 --> 00:52:27.050
Saddam Hussein was selectively
hitting on the oil market and

00:52:27.050 --> 00:52:30.800
not the natural gas market;
that explains those two markets.

00:52:30.800 --> 00:52:32.949
I wanted to talk briefly about
other futures.

00:52:32.949 --> 00:52:37.725
There's a gold futures market
and the gold futures

00:52:37.725 --> 00:52:43.767
market--this is an old clipping
I had of a very steady contango

00:52:43.767 --> 00:52:46.534
market.
That's because gold is very

00:52:46.534 --> 00:52:50.280
different than oil.
Gold is in storage.

00:52:50.280 --> 00:52:53.190
There's nothing to do with gold
except hold it.

00:52:53.190 --> 00:52:54.789
You don't burn it.
That's the difference;

00:52:54.789 --> 00:52:58.335
oil you burn it and it's gone,
so we don't have much around

00:52:58.335 --> 00:53:01.880
and we're always vulnerable to
some supply interruption.

00:53:01.880 --> 00:53:04.080
But with gold,
there's no supply interruption;

00:53:04.080 --> 00:53:07.002
we don't burn gold;
it just sits there and we're

00:53:07.002 --> 00:53:10.742
holding this stuff.
We don't know what to do with

00:53:10.742 --> 00:53:13.238
that.
It can't really be in contango

00:53:13.238 --> 00:53:17.128
for very long because someone
who's holding gold is going to

00:53:17.128 --> 00:53:19.137
say,
hey if it's going down in the

00:53:19.137 --> 00:53:21.860
futures market I'm not going to
sit on this stuff;

00:53:21.860 --> 00:53:27.730
I'm going to sell it.
It stays in--did I say contango?

00:53:27.730 --> 00:53:30.739
If it's in backwardation people
would sell it.

00:53:30.739 --> 00:53:34.310
It stays very nicely in
contango and it's going up at

00:53:34.310 --> 00:53:37.700
the rate of interest.
The storage--there's a storage

00:53:37.700 --> 00:53:40.234
cost as well,
but I don't know how big that

00:53:40.234 --> 00:53:43.176
is for gold.
I guess you'd have to pay for a

00:53:43.176 --> 00:53:46.789
police force to defend your
gold--something like that.

00:53:46.789 --> 00:53:52.648
So, it must have some storage
costs, but it's a very simple

00:53:52.648 --> 00:53:57.800
market because it stays in
contango all the time.

00:53:57.800 --> 00:54:02.449
Copper futures--now copper is
different from gold because it's

00:54:02.449 --> 00:54:05.269
not--this is a 2004 clipping
again.

00:54:05.269 --> 00:54:09.456
Copper is an industrial
commodity that gets used up,

00:54:09.456 --> 00:54:13.806
so it suffers from supply
disruptions and it can--like

00:54:13.806 --> 00:54:17.090
oil--it can fall into
backwardation.

00:54:17.090 --> 00:54:23.239
Here, I should write these--did
I ever write these down?

00:54:23.239 --> 00:54:28.133
Contango, just to make sure,
is when futures prices are

00:54:28.133 --> 00:54:31.940
going up as the maturity--with
maturity;

00:54:31.940 --> 00:54:34.920
higher prices for more future
dates.

00:54:34.920 --> 00:54:43.599
Backwardation is when it's
going down.

00:54:43.599 --> 00:54:49.130
This is an example of a
backwardated market.

00:54:49.130 --> 00:54:53.070
The prices as we go out to
further and further--this is

00:54:53.070 --> 00:54:56.354
2004--when we go out to December
of that year,

00:54:56.354 --> 00:55:02.583
it's down from $139 to $136.
When we go out to December of

00:55:02.583 --> 00:55:07.820
the following year,
it's down to $118.

00:55:07.820 --> 00:55:10.780
Gold, by the way,
has gone up a lot too.

00:55:10.780 --> 00:55:13.423
There's been a lot of commodity
price increases that surprised

00:55:13.423 --> 00:55:15.240
us.
This is the federal funds

00:55:15.240 --> 00:55:19.534
futures--another clipping.
There's a futures market for

00:55:19.534 --> 00:55:25.120
the federal funds rate and it's
cash-settled because you can't

00:55:25.120 --> 00:55:30.568
deliver federal funds.
The settlement--the price shown

00:55:30.568 --> 00:55:34.440
is $100 minus the federal funds
rate.

00:55:34.440 --> 00:55:42.730
So back then--this is 2004--the
federal funds rate was about 5%.

00:55:42.730 --> 00:55:52.780
So, this looks like 5.25%,
so $100 minus $94.74 is 5.25%;

00:55:52.780 --> 00:55:58.029
that's what the federal funds
rate was expected to be in March

00:55:58.029 --> 00:56:01.886
of 2004.
Here you see that the federal

00:56:01.886 --> 00:56:07.363
funds rate was expected to
continue to decline at that

00:56:07.363 --> 00:56:09.859
time.
This market can go either way

00:56:09.859 --> 00:56:13.428
because you don't store federal
funds, so there's no fair value

00:56:13.428 --> 00:56:16.480
calculation like there are with
the other markets.

00:56:16.480 --> 00:56:21.929
It reflects the expectations of
future interest rates.

00:56:21.929 --> 00:56:24.967
Right now, I don't--I should
have gotten today's,

00:56:24.967 --> 00:56:28.574
but I think the federal funds
futures market is predicting

00:56:28.574 --> 00:56:32.738
right now,
with the federal funds rate at

00:56:32.738 --> 00:56:38.750
2.25%, the federal funds
market--this would be $97.75,

00:56:38.750 --> 00:56:41.116
or $100 minus 2.25%;
or it would be close to that

00:56:41.116 --> 00:56:43.039
and it would be going down with
time.

00:56:43.039 --> 00:56:47.821
People are expecting the Fed to
cut interest rates--I'm sorry,

00:56:47.821 --> 00:56:51.897
these numbers would be going
up, but I don't have the

00:56:51.897 --> 00:56:56.422
clipping for today.
I just finally wanted to talk

00:56:56.422 --> 00:57:01.305
about home price futures,
which is a market that I've

00:57:01.305 --> 00:57:07.690
gotten involved with creating at
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.

00:57:07.690 --> 00:57:10.309
I got involved with them
because I have a price index.

00:57:10.309 --> 00:57:14.644
My colleague and I,
Karl Case, who's a professor at

00:57:14.644 --> 00:57:18.632
Wellesley College--he and I,
in the late 1980s,

00:57:18.632 --> 00:57:23.110
created a home price index.
This was our research;

00:57:23.110 --> 00:57:29.805
we put it out as a working
paper here at Yale twenty years

00:57:29.805 --> 00:57:31.760
ago.
From the beginning,

00:57:31.760 --> 00:57:35.115
we thought that the real
importance of having a home

00:57:35.115 --> 00:57:40.420
price index is for trading.
We live in a world where people

00:57:40.420 --> 00:57:46.005
don't trade--there's no
international market for real

00:57:46.005 --> 00:57:49.857
estate.
It's quite remarkable that

00:57:49.857 --> 00:57:55.840
there is not because real estate
is a huge asset class.

00:57:55.840 --> 00:58:01.619
The value of single-family
homes in this country is about

00:58:01.619 --> 00:58:07.502
30% bigger than the value of the
stock market in the U.S.;

00:58:07.502 --> 00:58:12.869
yet, we see so much talk about
the stock market.

00:58:12.869 --> 00:58:17.431
When we started in 1988 we
realized not only was there no

00:58:17.431 --> 00:58:22.467
market for single family homes,
except the very local market,

00:58:22.467 --> 00:58:26.920
there was also no price index
for single family homes.

00:58:26.920 --> 00:58:32.050
It's just sometimes amazing how
undeveloped things are.

00:58:32.050 --> 00:58:35.344
Here we are in the twentieth
century, everything is

00:58:35.344 --> 00:58:39.401
computerized and all that,
but you just want to know what

00:58:39.401 --> 00:58:43.750
home prices have been doing in
the United States in the late

00:58:43.750 --> 00:58:48.420
1980s and you couldn't find out.
There were some indexes,

00:58:48.420 --> 00:58:52.774
but they were rather poor,
we thought, and not very

00:58:52.774 --> 00:58:57.213
reliable.
We did our econometric work and

00:58:57.213 --> 00:59:04.110
devised a method of repeat sales
method of home price indexes.

00:59:04.110 --> 00:59:09.358
I wrote a book in 1993 called
Macro Markets about--it

00:59:09.358 --> 00:59:13.539
talked a lot about index number
construction.

00:59:13.539 --> 00:59:17.422
I said in the book that we need
to devise a home price index

00:59:17.422 --> 00:59:21.700
that is as close as possible to
something like the S&amp;P 500,

00:59:21.700 --> 00:59:26.034
which is a stock price index.
The problem with home prices is

00:59:26.034 --> 00:59:29.440
we have a much bigger
non-trading problem.

00:59:29.440 --> 00:59:33.988
The S&amp;P 500 is not very
out-of-date because stocks

00:59:33.988 --> 00:59:39.224
usually don't go untraded for
more than a few minutes or maybe

00:59:39.224 --> 00:59:43.447
a few hours at times.
With homes, the typical home

00:59:43.447 --> 00:59:47.823
doesn't trade every ten years,
so we have a huge non-trading

00:59:47.823 --> 00:59:50.773
problem.
What we did is we created an

00:59:50.773 --> 00:59:55.117
index that was as close as
possible to a stock price index

00:59:55.117 --> 00:59:59.079
so that it could be traded on a
financial market.

00:59:59.079 --> 01:00:01.676
Then I had a student here,
Allan Weiss,

01:00:01.676 --> 01:00:05.434
who said, why don't we get
going and get--my student was

01:00:05.434 --> 01:00:08.926
graduating;
he was an SOM student--MBA

01:00:08.926 --> 01:00:12.021
student.
He was graduating and he

01:00:12.021 --> 01:00:17.439
thought we should produce these
indexes for sale for use in

01:00:17.439 --> 01:00:21.550
financial markets,
so he wanted to do it.

01:00:21.550 --> 01:00:24.408
He set up our company,
Case Shiller Weiss,

01:00:24.408 --> 01:00:26.500
Incorporated,
and he ran it.

01:00:26.500 --> 01:00:29.049
Now, Case and I were just on
the advisory--well,

01:00:29.049 --> 01:00:31.761
we were on the board of
directors, but we were just

01:00:31.761 --> 01:00:34.329
advising the operations.
I was so proud of him;

01:00:34.329 --> 01:00:38.933
my student created the
Case-Shiller Home Price Indexes

01:00:38.933 --> 01:00:43.375
and we started publishing them.
Then in early 1990s,

01:00:43.375 --> 01:00:48.178
we traveled to all the futures
markets, proposing to them that

01:00:48.178 --> 01:00:52.510
they create home price futures
based on our indexes.

01:00:52.510 --> 01:00:59.840
It was disappointing;
we couldn't get anyone to do it.

01:00:59.840 --> 01:01:01.840
I thought we had such a strong
case.

01:01:01.840 --> 01:01:04.679
Shouldn't there be a futures
market?

01:01:04.679 --> 01:01:07.986
We went to the--I mentioned the
coffee, sugar,

01:01:07.986 --> 01:01:11.812
cocoa--we tried them all.
So, we'd go to these guys and

01:01:11.812 --> 01:01:14.480
they're trading coffee,
sugar, and cocoa.

01:01:14.480 --> 01:01:19.789
I said, look coffee is nice,
everyone wants their cup in the

01:01:19.789 --> 01:01:25.010
morning, but we're talking about
twenty trillion dollars of

01:01:25.010 --> 01:01:28.055
unhedged risk.
Most households in the United

01:01:28.055 --> 01:01:31.210
States--that's what they own.
The typical household--they

01:01:31.210 --> 01:01:35.370
don't own much stock;
they own real estate and they

01:01:35.370 --> 01:01:38.813
can't hedge it.
I think we had the most

01:01:38.813 --> 01:01:42.289
progress with the Chicago Board
of Trade;

01:01:42.289 --> 01:01:45.989
they actually did some research
with us.

01:01:45.989 --> 01:01:49.052
The funny thing that happened
was that CBOT did research in

01:01:49.052 --> 01:01:51.902
1994 on whether they should set
up a futures market for

01:01:51.902 --> 01:01:54.713
single-family homes.
The basic conclusion--they made

01:01:54.713 --> 01:01:57.552
a lot of phone calls--that's how
they did research--asking

01:01:57.552 --> 01:01:59.940
people,
are you worried about your home

01:01:59.940 --> 01:02:03.782
price falling and would you like
to be able to hedge the risk in

01:02:03.782 --> 01:02:07.198
the futures market the way
farmers do in the agricultural

01:02:07.198 --> 01:02:10.319
market?
Basically, the answer was no

01:02:10.319 --> 01:02:13.989
and people said,
I don't worry about my home

01:02:13.989 --> 01:02:17.482
price falling.
So, they didn't want to start a

01:02:17.482 --> 01:02:21.304
market because they thought--but
I was going around saying,

01:02:21.304 --> 01:02:24.050
don't you know?
There's no law of economics

01:02:24.050 --> 01:02:26.130
saying that home prices don't
fall.

01:02:26.130 --> 01:02:29.233
They did--they have fallen;
they fell a lot in the

01:02:29.233 --> 01:02:32.289
Depression and they could do it
again.

01:02:32.289 --> 01:02:36.471
So, why don't people want to
have a market that would--they

01:02:36.471 --> 01:02:39.159
don't just go steadily up.
But people said,

01:02:39.159 --> 01:02:40.960
well the Depression--that was
so long ago;

01:02:40.960 --> 01:02:44.858
we can't remember that.
So, we couldn't seem to get

01:02:44.858 --> 01:02:49.131
anyone focused on it.
I think there's something about

01:02:49.131 --> 01:02:54.447
this that we learned about the
origins of our current economic

01:02:54.447 --> 01:02:57.187
situation.
We went around to a lot of

01:02:57.187 --> 01:03:00.339
people trying to get them
interested in hedging real

01:03:00.339 --> 01:03:03.133
estate prices.
Remember, the purpose of

01:03:03.133 --> 01:03:06.660
futures markets is not gambling;
it's hedging;

01:03:06.660 --> 01:03:10.198
it's protecting yourself.
I should write that term on the

01:03:10.198 --> 01:03:16.309
board as well.
Hedging--I hope I made this

01:03:16.309 --> 01:03:18.980
clear.
If you are running--let's go

01:03:18.980 --> 01:03:22.304
back to wheat.
If you have a warehouse full of

01:03:22.304 --> 01:03:26.556
wheat, you are a wheat
warehouser and you are like a

01:03:26.556 --> 01:03:29.730
stable business.
So, what do you do?

01:03:29.730 --> 01:03:31.989
You don't know what the price
of wheat is going to do;

01:03:31.989 --> 01:03:33.760
it goes up and down
internationally.

01:03:33.760 --> 01:03:36.692
So, what do you do?
You sell it in the futures

01:03:36.692 --> 01:03:40.324
market and that means you've
hedged your risk of wheat

01:03:40.324 --> 01:03:42.474
prices.
If wheat prices go down,

01:03:42.474 --> 01:03:46.258
true the value of the stuff in
storage that you own is going to

01:03:46.258 --> 01:03:48.791
go down,
but offsetting that is your

01:03:48.791 --> 01:03:51.549
futures contract price,
which will go up,

01:03:51.549 --> 01:03:54.099
and that hedging will protect
you.

01:03:54.099 --> 01:03:58.860
You have reduced risk of your
business and this is done a lot.

01:03:58.860 --> 01:04:00.535
Holbrook Working,
in the reading,

01:04:00.535 --> 01:04:03.320
talks about that.
So, farmers also can hedge;

01:04:03.320 --> 01:04:06.927
they've got wheat growing in
the fields and they're worried

01:04:06.927 --> 01:04:10.969
about the price they can sell it
at, so let's lock it in today;

01:04:10.969 --> 01:04:13.630
let's sell in the futures
market.

01:04:13.630 --> 01:04:17.627
If the price of wheat declines,
your short position in the

01:04:17.627 --> 01:04:21.205
futures market will appreciate
and offset your loss,

01:04:21.205 --> 01:04:26.901
so you want to hedge your risk.
We went around asking people,

01:04:26.901 --> 01:04:33.719
don't you want to hedge your
risk in the real estate market?

01:04:33.719 --> 01:04:35.844
Unfortunately,
people are rather confused

01:04:35.844 --> 01:04:38.500
about that and they're not used
to hedging that.

01:04:38.500 --> 01:04:46.036
Anyway, with the recent boom in
home prices, we were able--we

01:04:46.036 --> 01:04:53.699
finally approached the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in 2006 and

01:04:53.699 --> 01:04:56.426
said,
we want to work with you to

01:04:56.426 --> 01:05:00.270
create--try to create--a futures
market for single family homes.

01:05:00.270 --> 01:05:07.340
They said, okay let's try it.
So, this was what we did in May

01:05:07.340 --> 01:05:10.023
of 2006;
we created a futures

01:05:10.023 --> 01:05:14.823
market--not the very first,
there was an attempt in London

01:05:14.823 --> 01:05:19.103
in 1991 that failed,
but we were essentially the

01:05:19.103 --> 01:05:23.444
first futures market for
single-family homes in the

01:05:23.444 --> 01:05:27.417
United States.
This market has been in

01:05:27.417 --> 01:05:31.869
backwardation almost from the
first day.

01:05:31.869 --> 01:05:36.474
When we opened the market in
May of 2006, our market maker,

01:05:36.474 --> 01:05:40.920
who was brought in by the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange,

01:05:40.920 --> 01:05:44.890
thought like everyone else who
reads the newspapers--well,

01:05:44.890 --> 01:05:49.845
home prices just always go up.
So, the market maker put out a

01:05:49.845 --> 01:05:55.477
bid-asked that implied contango
in the market--that home prices

01:05:55.477 --> 01:05:59.086
would go up.
The market maker quickly

01:05:59.086 --> 01:06:03.860
learned that there was no
market--contango market.

01:06:03.860 --> 01:06:09.035
After losing a huge amount of
money, he pushed his bid-asked

01:06:09.035 --> 01:06:14.122
spreads into the backwardation
range and left it there ever

01:06:14.122 --> 01:06:17.227
since.
This shows the backwardation in

01:06:17.227 --> 01:06:21.252
the futures market recently,
but it's been this way for a

01:06:21.252 --> 01:06:24.051
couple years now.
So, what's going on in the

01:06:24.051 --> 01:06:26.788
housing market?
I think that what has been

01:06:26.788 --> 01:06:30.730
happening is that newspapers,
and real estate agents,

01:06:30.730 --> 01:06:34.442
and lots of
commentators--people you see on

01:06:34.442 --> 01:06:40.010
the news--have been telling us
that home prices always go up;

01:06:40.010 --> 01:06:45.719
they've never fallen and don't
worry.

01:06:45.719 --> 01:06:48.701
A lot of casual people have
believed that,

01:06:48.701 --> 01:06:52.845
but the kind of people who
trade in futures markets didn't

01:06:52.845 --> 01:06:56.190
believe it, even going back to
early 2006.

01:06:56.190 --> 01:06:59.580
People who are ready to put
their money on the line have

01:06:59.580 --> 01:07:03.340
been predicting a decline in
home prices now for two years.

01:07:03.340 --> 01:07:07.129
You can see what dramatic
declines are being predicted in

01:07:07.129 --> 01:07:09.930
our futures market.
I have it for various

01:07:09.930 --> 01:07:12.099
cities--Boston,
Chicago, Denver.

01:07:12.099 --> 01:07:16.014
We have separate markets for
each of the ten--of these ten

01:07:16.014 --> 01:07:18.074
cities--Las Vegas,
Los Angeles,

01:07:18.074 --> 01:07:21.440
Miami, New York,
San Diego and San Francisco.

01:07:21.440 --> 01:07:27.343
The worst market of them all is
Miami and this market is

01:07:27.343 --> 01:07:33.353
predicting almost a 35% home
price decline by November of

01:07:33.353 --> 01:07:36.903
2012.
The second worst--what is the

01:07:36.903 --> 01:07:39.195
second worst?
I can't quite read it;

01:07:39.195 --> 01:07:43.885
they kind of merged here.
There's a bunch of cities where

01:07:43.885 --> 01:07:48.010
the prediction is for a 20-25%
drop;

01:07:48.010 --> 01:07:52.203
the best city of all is
Chicago, but even there they're

01:07:52.203 --> 01:07:55.461
predicting a 7% drop.
So, we've seen a lot of

01:07:55.461 --> 01:07:59.175
backwardation in that market.
I think this is reflecting the

01:07:59.175 --> 01:08:01.570
unusual economic circumstance
we're in.

01:08:01.570 --> 01:08:06.570
Finally, this is my last slide;
this shows the S&amp;P

01:08:06.570 --> 01:08:12.036
Case-Shiller Home Price Index.
That line is the actually home

01:08:12.036 --> 01:08:15.179
price index and it has these
jumps in it every month;

01:08:15.179 --> 01:08:17.659
that's because it's a monthly
index.

01:08:17.659 --> 01:08:21.685
We only publish it every month,
but you can see that it's been

01:08:21.685 --> 01:08:24.260
smooth.
It was increasing until around

01:08:24.260 --> 01:08:27.957
the time we started the futures
market and then it's been

01:08:27.957 --> 01:08:30.399
declining at an accelerating
rate.

01:08:30.399 --> 01:08:36.160
We are now down in real terms
about 15% nationwide on home

01:08:36.160 --> 01:08:39.899
prices, which peaked in early
2006.

01:08:39.899 --> 01:08:44.343
This is the futures price that
we've had and that's for the

01:08:44.343 --> 01:08:48.479
closest futures contract--the
nearest to expiration.

01:08:48.479 --> 01:08:51.100
We're hoping to get a lot of
publicity for this because we

01:08:51.100 --> 01:08:53.170
thought this was a very
interesting number.

01:08:53.170 --> 01:08:57.599
This is futures market price
for homes and it moves around

01:08:57.599 --> 01:09:00.111
day by day.
All those little wiggles

01:09:00.111 --> 01:09:03.739
reflect new information that
came in on a particular day.

01:09:03.739 --> 01:09:06.680
Unfortunately,
we have not been able to get

01:09:06.680 --> 01:09:10.600
much attention for this number,
but there's been a lot of

01:09:10.600 --> 01:09:14.449
attention to the S&amp;P
Case-Shiller Home Price Indexes

01:09:14.449 --> 01:09:17.314
now.
In fact, we're getting

01:09:17.314 --> 01:09:23.020
newspaper stories all the time
written about our indexes,

01:09:23.020 --> 01:09:26.518
but they don't write about our
market, so we've had trouble

01:09:26.518 --> 01:09:28.630
getting a futures market
started.

01:09:28.630 --> 01:09:32.170
It's going, but it's going only
at a low level.

01:09:32.170 --> 01:09:35.944
I think that in the future this
will take off eventually and I

01:09:35.944 --> 01:09:39.720
think that we'll have futures
markets for many more things.

01:09:39.720 --> 01:09:42.851
Eventually, we'll have a
futures market for New Haven as

01:09:42.851 --> 01:09:44.913
well.
Right now, New Haven is too

01:09:44.913 --> 01:09:47.439
small to warrant its own futures
market.

01:09:47.439 --> 01:09:50.145
So, I was thinking,
well someone in New Haven could

01:09:50.145 --> 01:09:52.850
just buy two--if you wanted to
hedge your house,

01:09:52.850 --> 01:09:56.164
you'd sell two New York
contracts and one Boston

01:09:56.164 --> 01:09:58.587
contract.
I'm sort of interpolating

01:09:58.587 --> 01:10:02.276
between New York and Boston,
but eventually we have to do

01:10:02.276 --> 01:10:06.361
better than that and I'm hopeful
that there will be a day in my

01:10:06.361 --> 01:10:10.050
lifetime when we'll see all
cities of the world traded on

01:10:10.050 --> 01:10:12.667
futures market.
In my new book,

01:10:12.667 --> 01:10:15.626
Subprime Solution,
I also claim,

01:10:15.626 --> 01:10:19.130
and I think I have some basis
to say this,

01:10:19.130 --> 01:10:22.102
that it will help reduce
bubbles and help reduce this

01:10:22.102 --> 01:10:24.128
kind of instability.
Next period,

01:10:24.128 --> 01:10:27.588
we're going to talk about
options and then we have only

01:10:27.588 --> 01:10:31.634
one more lecture;
the last lecture on the

01:10:31.634 --> 01:10:33.500
democratization of finance.
 

